{
  "text": "Besides the boundary control of hyperbolic PDE systems (see [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , it was soon recognised that the backstepping approach can also provide systematic solutions for the control of PDE-ODE systems. In the pioneering work [CITATION_3] , the backstepping method was applied to the stabilisation of a PDE-ODE cascade, in which the PDE iscan be found (see e.g. [CITATION_4] . Examples for coupled PDE-ODE systems are pinched cables with a tip mass at the free end (see e.g. [CITATION_5] , heavy chains or ropes with a load (see e.g. [CITATION_6] , fluid transmission lines (see e.g. [CITATION_7] or oscillations in oil well drilling (see e.g. Sagert, Di Meglio, [CITATION_8] . A first solution for a heat equation coupled with an ODE can be found in [CITATION_9] . Therein, the coupling in the PDE appears at the unactuated boundary. The same type of coupling was considered in [CITATION_10] for a wave equation. Another important problem is the stabilisation of coupled PDE-ODE systems with an in-domain coupling in the PDE. Solutions for a heat equation can be found in [CITATION_11] , whereas [CITATION_12] deal with a wave equation.",
